[BID 2C] Your partner opens 1\H, showing an opening hand and at least five hearts. ⟦Game-forcing. You bid your five-card \C suit at the two level, promising 13 or more, before you get around to supporting partner's major.⟧
[BID 4D] Partner rebids notrump, showing a balanced hand within the game force. ⟦You jump to a new suit. With the fit established, this is a cue-bid showing your \DA and a slam interest, advertising to partner that your hand is packed with controls.⟧
[BID 5D] Partner takes charge with Roman Key Card Blackwood, asking how many of the five keycards, the four aces plus the trump king, your side holds. ⟦You answer honestly. Sitting with all three side aces yourself, your reply confirms the keycards partner needs; nothing is missing.⟧
[BID Pass] Partner counts the keycards and places the contract in six of the major. ⟦You pass; 6\H is the final contract.⟧
[show NS]This is the point worth keeping: the hand loaded with aces should shout its controls, and here your 4D cue-bid did exactly that, letting the partnership confirm every keycard before committing. Because you owned all the aces, there was never an ace off the top, and the small slam brought in twelve tricks. Show your controls, answer the key-card ask straight, and slams like this land where they belong.}
